issue.title: Fix: clear duplicate-casing errors after case-only file renames on Windows (closes #261995)
issue.body: On case-insensitive file systems (Windows for example) renaming a file by only changing its letter-case ~ for example `page1.js` => `Page1.js` ~ confuses `tsserver`. It continues to hold both casings in the program and surfaces errors such as: The error persists until the user manually restarts the TS server or reloads VS Code (see bug #261995). ### RCA File-watcher stacks don‚Äôt always emit a delete => create sequence for a case-only rename on case-insensitive FSs. `tsserver` therefore never drops the old path and thinks the file is duplicated. ### Testing * Verified on Windows 11. ### Files changed * `extensions/typescript-language-features/src/languageFeatures/updatePathsOnRename.ts` * `extensions/typescript-language-features/src/typeScriptServiceClientHost.ts` --- Closes #261995

Pretty tough to find artists that specialize in a certain niche. E.g. I want a list of artists that usually draw cat girls (a random number would be maybe, artists with at least 50 pieces of art tagged as 'cat girl'). I can click around in the cat girl tag, but that's likely to lead me to a bunch of artists that have only drawn a cat girl once. 

**Describe the solution you'd like**

A way to filter artists based on how much of X they have in their gallery. E.g. there's a box you can type a number in + specify a tag, and artists that don't meet that threshold don't appear.

Manually finding artists. 

**Additional context**

N/A, thanks if you choose this.

comment.body:
Hello üëã 

Grabber, while it has some local features, mostly just forwards requests to the website to find results. So unless a given website has a way to return tags that have X number of images with another tag in their search results, that seem like a pretty complex thing to do.
The alternative on Grabber's side would be to load _all_ results, and only then filter them based on the tag criteria, but that seem quite the intensive thing to do üòÖ

On the other hand, some websites do provide some cross-tag search feature, like Danbooru. Maybe that would help you?

- Bundles Chart.js via `chart.js/auto` and all app scripts
- Outputs `dist/mortgage-calc.bundle.min.js` (+ sourcemap)
- Webflow snippets:
  - `snippets/webflow_head.html` ‚Äî CSS links for Page Head
  - `snippets/webflow-embed-no-scripts.min.html` ‚Äî Embed (no scripts)
  - `snippets/webflow_footer_bundle_pinned.html` ‚Äî Footer script (pinned)
  - `snippets/webflow_footer_bundle_dev.html` ‚Äî Footer script (dev)

## How to use
1. `npm i && npm run build`
2. Commit **dist/** so jsDelivr can serve it:
   ```bash
   git add dist/mortgage-calc.bundle.min.js dist/mortgage-calc.bundle.min.js.map
   git commit -m "build: bundle vv1.0.0"
   ```
3. Tag and push:
   ```bash
   git tag v1.0.0
   git push origin v1.0.0
   ```
4. Webflow **Footer** (pinned):
   ```html
   <script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/getmarketingandai/hycalc@v1.0.0/dist/mortgage-calc.bundle.min.js" defer></script>
   ```

## Notes
- Keep using the **no-scripts** embed so all logic comes from the bundle.
- Dev flow: build, commit `dist/` to `main`, and use the `@main` footer snippet.

issue.title: Feature: Update and modify qualifications
issue.body:
### Epic

Qualification Management

### Story Points (Estimate)

8

### User Story

As a user, I want to be able to view all of my existing qualifications on a summary page so that I can select the relevant qualification.

As a user, I want to be able to edit the summary information for each qualification so that it correctly reflects any changes.

As a user, I want to be able to add child elements (i.e. year, module, assessment) for each qualification, so that the structure reflects my qualification.

As a user, I want to be able to set different calculation settings for each hierarchy so that differences in assessments and modules are handled correctly.


### Background/Context

Users should be able to fill out all relevant information related to their degree in a reasonable structure to represent how their qualification is broken down.

Users should be able to update settings on a global, or per-qualification level.

### Acceptance Criteria

Given I am a logged in user and I have navigated to the qualifications tab, I should see a list of all existing qualifications with summary information (name, type, predicted/actual/target grade).

Given I have selected a qualification from the above list, I should be able to view and edit settings related to the summary information, plus specific qualification-related settings (number of credits, etc).

Given I have selected a qualification, I should be able to view all immediate child elements with similar summary information.

Given I have selected a child element, I should be able to view and edit settings, and view the next immediate child information (years -> modules -> assessments)

issue.title: Consolidate Authentication URLs into users app
issue.body:
Task: Consolidate Authentication URLs into users app

Goal

  • Move all authentication & account endpoints into users/urls.py.

  • Mount them under a single prefix: /api/v1/auth/.

  • Remove/stop exposing auth endpoints from core/urls.py (except global docs/health/admin).

  • Keep route names stable (or provide a clear mapping) and avoid duplicate paths.

New Endpoint Map (final contract)

Action | Method | New Path | View | Auth -- | -- | -- | -- | -- Sign up | POST | /api/v1/auth/register/ | UserRegistrationView | No Log in (JWT create) | POST | /api/v1/auth/jwt/create/ | CustomTokenObtainPairView | No Refresh access | POST | /api/v1/auth/jwt/refresh/ | TokenRefreshView | No Log out (blacklist) | POST | /api/v1/auth/jwt/logout/ | TokenBlacklistView | Yes Current user | GET | /api/v1/auth/me/ | MeView (or existing profile view) | Yes Request password reset | POST | /api/v1/auth/password/reset/ | CustomPasswordResetView | No Confirm password reset | POST | /api/v1/auth/password/reset/confirm/ | CustomPasswordResetConfirmView | No Verify email | GET | /api/v1/auth/verify-email/// | VerifyEmailView | No OAuth login (optional) | POST | /api/v1/auth/oauth/login/ | OAuthTokenObtainPairView | No

If you still need Djoser routes, mount them beneath a sub-prefix to avoid collisions, e.g. /api/v1/auth/djoser/....

What to change

1) core/urls.py ‚Äì remove auth routes and mount users auth block once

Before (auth endpoints declared here)
After ‚Äì keep global stuff + include users under /api/v1/auth/:

# core/urls.py (final shape)
from django.contrib import admin
from django.urls import path, include
from django.conf import settings
from django.conf.urls.static import static
from .healthcheck import elasticsearch_healthcheck
from drf_spectacular.views import SpectacularAPIView, SpectacularRedocView, SpectacularSwaggerView

urlpatterns = [
    path('admin/', admin.site.urls),

    # Versioned API
    path('api/v1/auth/', include('users.urls')),            # <-- all auth lives here now
    path('api/v1/projects/', include('projects.urls')),
    path('api/v1/startups/', include('startups.urls')),
    path('api/v1/investors/', include('investors.urls')),

    # Docs
    path('api/schema/', SpectacularAPIView.as_view(), name='schema'),
    path('api/schema/swagger-ui/', SpectacularSwaggerView.as_view(url_name='schema'), name='swagger-ui'),
    path('api/schema/redoc/', SpectacularRedocView.as_view(url_name='schema'), name='redoc'),

    # Health & allauth (if needed)
    path('health/elasticsearch/', elasticsearch_healthcheck),
    path('accounts/', include('allauth.urls')),
]

if settings.DEBUG:
    urlpatterns += static(settings.STATIC_URL, document_root=settings.STATIC_ROOT)
    urlpatterns += static(settings.MEDIA_URL, document_root=settings.MEDIA_ROOT)

Remove any auth paths from api_urlpatterns in core/urls.py (e.g. auth/register/, auth/jwt/create/, oauth/login/, verify-email/...).

2) users/urls.py ‚Äì expose the full auth surface

Replace its contents with:

# users/urls.py
from django.urls import path, include
from rest_framework_simplejwt.views import TokenRefreshView, TokenBlacklistView
from .views import (
    CustomTokenObtainPairView,
    UserRegistrationView,
    VerifyEmailView,
    OAuthTokenObtainPairView,
    CustomPasswordResetView,
    CustomPasswordResetConfirmView,
    MeView,  # implement if not present (returns current user)
)

urlpatterns = [
    # Sign up
    path('register/', UserRegistrationView.as_view(), name='user_register'),

    # JWT Auth
    path('jwt/create/', CustomTokenObtainPairView.as_view(), name='jwt-create'),
    path('jwt/refresh/', TokenRefreshView.as_view(), name='jwt-refresh'),
    path('jwt/logout/', TokenBlacklistView.as_view(), name='token_blacklist'),

    # Current user
    path('me/', MeView.as_view(), name='auth_me'),

    # Password reset (custom)
    path('password/reset/', CustomPasswordResetView.as_view(), name='custom_reset_password'),
    path('password/reset/confirm/', CustomPasswordResetConfirmView.as_view(), name='custom_reset_password_confirm'),

    # Email verification
    path('verify-email/<int:user_id>/<str:token>/', VerifyEmailView.as_view(), name='verify-email'),

    # OAuth (optional)
    path('oauth/login/', OAuthTokenObtainPairView.as_view(), name='oauth_login'),

    # Djoser (optional; keep namespaced to avoid overlap)
    # path('djoser/', include('djoser.urls')),
    # path('djoser/', include('djoser.urls.jwt')),
]

If you still need login/ as a legacy alias, add path('login/', CustomTokenObtainPairView.as_view(), name='custom_login') but prefer /jwt/create/.

3) Implement MeView (if you don‚Äôt have it yet)

# users/views.py (snippet)
from rest_framework.views import APIView
from rest_framework.permissions import IsAuthenticated
from rest_framework.response import Response
from .serializers import CurrentUserSerializer  # create a simple serializer for the user

class MeView(APIView):
    permission_classes = [IsAuthenticated]

    def get(self, request):
        return Response(CurrentUserSerializer(request.user).data)

Breaking-change notes / Migration Guide

  • Old: POST /api/v1/auth/jwt/logout/ in core/urls.py
    New: unchanged path, now served from users/urls.py.

  • Old: POST /api/v1/auth/reset_password/ and reset_password_confirm/ in users/urls.py
    New: standardized to /password/reset/ and /password/reset/confirm/.

  • Old: GET /api/v1/auth/verify-email/<user_id>/<token>/ in core/urls.py
    New: same path under users/urls.py.

  • Old: POST /api/v1/oauth/login/ in core/urls.py
    New: POST /api/v1/auth/oauth/login/.

If the frontend already calls the old paths, add temporary redirects or keep thin alias routes for one release.

Tests to update

  • URL reversing: update reverse() calls to the new names/paths if changed (auth_me, user_register, jwt-create, etc.).

  • Integration tests: ensure all endpoints reachable at /api/v1/auth/....

  • Swagger tests (if any): schema still includes the endpoints and security (Bearer).

Swagger/OpenAPI

  • Ensure extend_schema tags = ["Auth"] on these views.

  • After changes: python manage.py spectacular --file openapi-schema.yaml should pass.

Acceptance Criteria

  • All routes listed above are available under /api/v1/auth/....

  • No duplicate auth routes remain in core/urls.py.

  • Existing JWT behavior unchanged (create/refresh/blacklist).

  • GET /api/v1/auth/me/ returns the authenticated user.

  • Password reset request/confirm works on new paths.

  • Swagger shows the updated paths.

Rollback plan

If issues arise, temporarily re-include the prior auth paths in core/urls.py behind a feature flag (e.g., AUTH_URLS_FALLBACK=true) while fixing the new routing, then remove once stable.

Proper description added to the readme file.

Fix no-enum-constexpr-conversion compilation error in DX12 backend with clang-cl (#696)

The warning suppression -Wno-enum-constexpr-conversion no longer works
on recent Clang versions because the warning it used to suppress has been
promoted to an error that cannot be disabled
(see https://github.com/llvm/llvm-project/issues/59036).

Also, the previous error in RootParamsManager.cpp was due to converting -1
to a D3D12_DESCRIPTOR_RANGE_TYPE enum in a constexpr context. Clang rejects
this, but it allows the conversion for a regular const. The code has been
updated to use a const instead of constexpr, making the conversion valid.

Since the original issue that motivated the warning suppression no longer
applies, we can safely remove -Wno-enum-constexpr-conversion.
